Raw dev notes -- Personal AI Hooks: First Steps & Gotchas

Okay, so this past week has been all about getting my personal AI code hooks toolkit off the ground. I've been using AI assistants a lot at work, and there are some really useful patterns and scripts we've developed there. The idea behind `claude-hooks` is to extract those generic, non-organizational-specific bits and build a personal toolkit. I want to integrate AI directly into my own dev workflow, making it easier to get quick answers, refactor suggestions, or even just understand complex code without leaving my terminal. It's about making my personal coding life a bit smarter and more efficient.

The initial push was just getting the basic structure in place. I then focused on porting over a couple of key hooks. First up was the `rtk` hook, which I'd somehow missed in the very first commit. This one is super useful for generating reports or summaries based on code context. Along with it, I added `rtk_report.py`, which is the script that actually does the heavy lifting for those reports.

Then came the documentation phase, which turned out to be more critical than I expected. I had to add notes about a specific bug in the `rtk` hook where it was messing up output from `grep` or `find` commands. The workaround involved an `exclude_commands` setting, which felt a bit clunky but got the job done for now. Installation also proved to be a bit of a minefield. I had to document a "read-once copy-not-junction" approach – basically, don't symlink, just copy the files once – to avoid weird issues. Plus, there were considerations around `tiktoken` (the tokenization library) for managing API costs and limits, and another general `rtk` "gotcha" that needed explaining.

Later in the week, I pulled in another really handy hook: `smart-ask-bash`. This one is fantastic for getting AI help directly in the bash shell, like "how do I do X with Y command?" or "explain this error." It was a direct mirror from a team config I'd worked on, so it was mostly a copy-paste, but still required a bit of tweaking to make it truly generic.

Honestly, this whole process has been a mix of excitement and minor frustration. It's incredibly satisfying to build something for myself that I know will genuinely improve my workflow. But man, the little things really get you. That `grep`/`find` bug in `rtk` was a head-scratcher for a bit, and the installation quirks made me realize how much friction there can be even in a simple setup. It really hammered home the importance of good, clear documentation, even if the "user" is just future me. It also showed me that generalizing code from a specific context isn't always straightforward; you have to really think about dependencies and assumptions. Still, seeing these hooks come to life and knowing I'm building a powerful personal tool feels great.

Next up: Refine existing hooks and explore adding more AI-powered refactoring tools.
